         [01]Show

Setup Question	= Intel(R) Adaptive Boost Technology
Help String	= Enable/Disable IABT to improve performance by allowing higher multi-core turbo frequencies.  Operating within system power and temperature specifications when current, power and thermal headroom exists, please ensure quality cooling for the CPU before enabling the ABT function.

Offset	=2E9

         [01]Disabled
         [02]Enabled

Setup Question	= ASUS MultiCore Enhancement
Help String	= [Auto]: ASUS optimized core ratio Turbo and temperature settings at default processor speeds.  [Disabled]: Intel default Turbo core ratio settings.  [Enabled]: Optimized power and current thresholds for maintaining maximum performance.
Token	=2B97	// Do NOT change this line
Offset	=0E
Width	=01
BIOS Default	=[00]Disabled  Enforce All limits 
Options	=[01]Auto  Lets BIOS Optimize	// Move "*" to the desired Option
         *[00]Disabled  Enforce All limits
         [02]Enabled  Remove All limits

Setup Question	= SVID Behavior
Help String	= Programs the CPUs SVID behavior based on CPUs quality.  Default is based on Typical Scenario but the more optimistic the mode selected, the lower the temperature of the CPU.  Intels Fail Safe is the default behavior of the processor oblivious to the actual Motherboard design.
Token	=1E	// Do NOT change this line
Offset	=2BE
Width	=01
BIOS Default	=[00]Auto 
Options	=*[00]Auto	// Move "*" to the desired Option
         [01]Best-Case Scenario
         [02]Typical Scenario
         [03]Worst-Case Scenario
         [04]Intels Fail Safe

Setup Question	=   1-Core Ratio Limit
Help String	= The N-core ratio limit must be higher than or equal to the (N+1)-core ratio limit. (N stands for the number of CPU cores.)  The core ratio limit cannot be set to Auto when the core number is lower than N.  The biggest cores ratio limit must be lower than or equal to the second biggest cores ratio limit.

Setup Question	= Ring Down Bin
Help String	= Enable/Disable Ring Downbin feature. Enabled - CPU will down bin the ring ratio, which means the requested max ring ratio may not be observed. Disable - CPU will not down bin the ring ratio and the requested ring ratio limit will be observed. Default is Enabled. Please use caution when disabling this feature as it may result in overvoltaging of the CPU. Uses OC mailbox command 0x19.
Token	=36	// Do NOT change this line
Offset	=5E
Width	=01
BIOS Default	=[00]Auto 
Options	=*[00]Auto	// Move "*" to the desired Option
         [01]Disabled
         [02]Enabled

Setup Question	= CPU Load-line Calibration
Help String	= The load-line is defined by the Intel VRM specification and affects the level of voltage supplied to the processor. Higher load-line calibration settings result in reduced VDroop at the expense of voltage overshoot and will increase CPU temperatures due to higher voltage under load. Select from level 1 to 7 to adjust the load-line slope. Level 1 = greater Vdroop, Level = 7 minimum VDroop.    * Performance is dependent on the CPU model used. Do not remove the VRM heatsink.

         [02]Level 1

         [04]Level 3
         [05]Level 4:Recommended for OC
         [06]Level 5
         [07]Level 6
         [08]Level 7

Setup Question	= CPU Graphics Load-line Calibration
Help String	= The load-line is defined by the Intel VRM specification and affects the CPU Graphics power voltage. The CPU Graphics working voltage will decrease proportionally depending on the CPU Graphics loading. Higher levels of the load-line calibration can get a higher voltage and a better overclocking performance but increase the CPU Graphics and VRM thermal production. Select from level 1 to 7 to adjust the CPU Graphics power voltage from 100% to 15%.  * The boosted performance may vary depending on the CPU Graphics specification. Do not remove the thermal module.

Setup Question	= Short Duration Package Power Limit
Help String	= An Intel parameter known as [power limit 2] and specified in Watts. It is the second Intel power limit which provides protection when package power exceeds power limit 1. The default setting is 1.25 times power limit 1. According to Intel, the platform must support this value for up to 10msec when power consumption exceeds power limit 2. ASUS motherboards are engineered to support this duration for a longer time as required to facilitate overclocking.  Min.: 1   |   Max.: 4095

// Setup Question	= AVX2 Ratio Offset to per-core Ratio Limit
// Help String	= AVX2 Ratio Offset. Specifies number of bins to decrease AVX ratio vs. Per-Core Ratio. AVX is a more stressful workload, it is helpful to lower the AVX ratio to ensure maximum possible ratio for SSE workloads. Uses Mailbox MSR 0x150, cmd 0x1B. Range 0 - 31. 0 = No offset.
// Token	=1DE	// Do NOT change this line
// Offset	=2DD
// Width	=01
// BIOS Default	=[00]Auto 
// Options	=*[00]Auto	// Move "*" to the desired Option
//         [01]User Specify

// Setup Question	= AVX2 Ratio Offset Value
// Help String	= AVX2 Ratio Offset. Specifies number of bins to decrease AVX ratio vs. Per-Core Ratio. AVX is a more stressful workload, it is helpful to lower the AVX ratio to ensure maximum possible ratio for SSE workloads. Uses Mailbox MSR 0x150, cmd 0x1B. Range 0 - 31. 0 = No offset.
// Token	=1DF	// Do NOT change this line
// Offset	=2DE
// Width	=01
// BIOS Default	=<0> 
// Value	=<0>

Setup Question	= AVX512 Ratio Offset to per-core Ratio Limit
Help String	= AVX512 Ratio Offset. Specifies number of bins to decrease AVX ratio vs. Per-Core Ratio. AVX is a more stressful workload, it is helpful to lower the AVX ratio to ensure maximum possible ratio for SSE workloads. Uses Mailbox MSR 0x150, cmd 0x1B. Range 0 - 31. 0 = No offset.

BIOS Default	=[00]Auto

         [01]User Specify

Setup Question	= AVX512 Ratio Offset Value
Help String	= AVX512 Ratio Offset. Specifies number of bins to decrease AVX ratio vs. Per-Core Ratio. AVX is a more stressful workload, it is helpful to lower the AVX ratio to ensure maximum possible ratio for SSE workloads. Uses Mailbox MSR 0x150, cmd 0x1B. Range 0 - 31. 0 = No offset.
Token	=1E1	// Do NOT change this line
Offset	=2E0
Width	=01
BIOS Default	=<0> 
Value	=<0>

Setup Question	= AVX2 Voltage Guardband Scale Factor
Help String	= Controls the voltage guardband applied to AVX workloads. Range in 1/100 units, where 125=1.25 scale factor. The resulting final voltage guardband is default guardband * Scale Factor.  Therefore lower than 100 values reduces guardband while higher than 100 values increases guardband.
Token	=1E2	// Do NOT change this line
Offset	=2E1
Width	=01
BIOS Default	=[00]Auto 
Options	=*[00]Auto	// Move "*" to the desired Option
         [01]User Specify

Setup Question	= V-Max Stress
Help String	= If Enabled, Frequency may be clipped if the max voltage on the silicon is too high. Frequency will not be clipped if disabled.

         [02]Enabled

Setup Question	= Overclocking TVB
Help String	= Enable this to be able to draw temperature/frequency dependencies.  +1Boost Profile:  This setting will enable additional boost of one bin with the help of Auto Optimized Temperature Control.  +2Boost Profile:  This setting will enable additional boost of two bins with the help of Auto Optimized Temperature Control.
Token	=1E8	// Do NOT change this line
Offset	=2EA
Width	=01
BIOS Default	=[00]Auto 
Options	=*[00]Auto	// Move "*" to the desired Option
         [01]Disabled
         [02]Enabled
         [03]+1Boost Profile
         [04]+2Boost Profile

Setup Question	= Sata Interrupt Selection
Help String	= Select which interrupt will be available to OS. This option only takes effect if SATA controller is in RAID mode.  Msix: Message Signaled Interrupt: permits a device to allocate up to 2048 interrupts, with support for NVMe devices.  Msi: Message Signaled Interrupt: permits a device to allocate 1, 2, 4, 8, 16 or 32 interrupts, with support for NVMe devices.  Legacy: SATA interrupt support for legacy OS or AHCI storage devices.

Offset	=4C

Setup Question	= AVX2 Ratio Offset to per-core Ratio Limit
Help String	= AVX2 Ratio Offset. Specifies number of bins to decrease AVX ratio vs. Per-Core Ratio. AVX is a more stressful workload, it is helpful to lower the AVX ratio to ensure maximum possible ratio for SSE workloads. Uses Mailbox MSR 0x150, cmd 0x1B. Range 0 - 31. 0 = No offset.
Token	=101F	// Do NOT change this line
Offset	=1A9
Width	=01
BIOS Default	=<0> 
Value	=<0>

Setup Question	= AVX2 Voltage Guardband Scale Factor
Help String	= Controls the voltage guardband applied to AVX workloads. Range in 1/100 units, where 125=1.25 scale factor. The resulting final voltage guardband is default guardband * Scale Factor.  Therefore lower than 100 values reduces guardband while higher than 100 values increases guardband.
Token	=1020	// Do NOT change this line
Offset	=20B
Width	=01
BIOS Default	=<0> 
Value	=<0>

Setup Question	= TVB Ratio Clipping
Help String	= This service controls Core frequency reduction caused by high package temperatures for processors that implement the Intel Thermal Velocity Boost (TVB) feature. It is required to be disabled for supporting overclocking at frequencies higher than the default max turbo frequency. Default is disabled. Uses Overclocking Mailbox command 0x18/0x19.
Token	=1024	// Do NOT change this line
Offset	=31D
Width	=01
BIOS Default	=[00]Disabled 
Options	=*[00]Disabled	// Move "*" to the desired Option
         [01]Enabled

Setup Question	= Ring Down Bin
Help String	= Enable/Disable Ring Downbin feature. Enabled - CPU will down bin the ring ratio, which means the requested max ring ratio may not be observed. Disable - CPU will not down bin the ring ratio and the requested ring ratio limit will be observed. Default is Enabled. Please use caution when disabling this feature as it may result in overvoltaging of the CPU. Uses OC mailbox command 0x19.
Token	=104A	// Do NOT change this line
Offset	=1AC
Width	=01
BIOS Default	=[01]Enabled 
Options	=*[00]Disabled	// Move "*" to the desired Option
         [01]Enabled

Setup Question	=       When system is in working state
Help String	= [All On]: RGB LEDs and Onboard LEDs will behave normally.   [Stealth]: All LEDs will be disabled.   [Aura Only]: RGB LEDs will light up, while all onboard LEDs will be disabled.   [Aura Off]: Onboard LEDs behave normally, while RGB LEDs will be disabled.   The RGB Header(s) and Addressable RGB Header(s) will only work under the S0 (working) state.
